{"id":"2210.11448","submitter":"Sebastian Mizera","authors":"Sebastian Mizera","title":"Natural Boundaries for Scattering Amplitudes","comments":"38 pages","journal-ref":"SciPost Phys. 14, 101 (2023)","doi":"10.21468/SciPostPhys.14.5.101","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Singularities, such as poles and branch points, play a crucial role in\ninvestigating the analytic properties of scattering amplitudes that inform new\ncomputational techniques. In this note, we point out that scattering amplitudes\ncan also have another class of singularities called natural boundaries of\nanalyticity. They create a barrier beyond which analytic continuation cannot be\nperformed. More concretely, we use unitarity to show that $2 \\to 2$ scattering\namplitudes in theories with a mass gap can have a natural boundary on the\nsecond sheet of the lightest threshold cut. There, an infinite number of\nladder-type Landau singularities densely accumulates on the real axis in the\ncenter-of-mass energy plane. We argue that natural boundaries are generic\nfeatures of higher-multiplicity scattering amplitudes in gapped theories.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 20 Oct 2022 17:49:05 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 7 Jan 2023 17:42:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-10"}
